05684nam a22007215i 9780822386711DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223867117 a10.1515/97808223867112doi  a(DE-B1597)552438  a(OCoLC)841913960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGN406b.M38 2005 7aSOC0190002bisacsh04a306.4/622200aMateriality /cDaniel Miller. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b7 b&w photos, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tMateriality: An Introduction -- tObjects in the Mirror Appear Closer Than They Are -- tA Materialist Approach to Materiality -- tSome Properties of Art and Culture: Ontologies of the Image and Economies of Exchange -- tSticky Subjects and Sticky Objects: The Substance of African Christian Healing -- tDoes Money Matter? Abstraction and Substitution in Alternative Financial Forms -- tThe Materiality of Finance Theory -- tSigns Are Not the Garb of Meaning: On the Social Analysis of Material Things -- tMateriality and Cognition: The Changing Face of Things -- tBeyond Mediation: Three New Material Registers and Their Consequences -- tThings Happen: Or, From Which Moment Does That Object Come? -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout history and across social and cultural contexts, most systems of belief-whether religious or secular-have ascribed wisdom to those who see reality as that which transcends the merely material. Yet, as the studies collected here show, the immaterial is not easily separated from the material. Humans are defined, to an extraordinary degree, by their expressions of immaterial ideals through material forms. The essays in Materiality explore varied manifestations of materiality from ancient times to the present. In assessing the fundamental role of materiality in shaping humanity, they signal the need to decenter the social within social anthropology in order to make room for the material.Considering topics as diverse as theology, technology, finance, and art, the contributors-most of whom are anthropologists-examine the many different ways in which materiality has been understood and the consequences of these differences. Their case studies show that the latest forms of financial trading instruments can be compared with the oldest ideals of ancient Egypt, that the promise of software can be compared with an age-old desire for an unmediated relationship to divinity. Whether focusing on the theology of Islamic banking, Australian Aboriginal art, derivatives trading in Japan, or textiles that respond directly to their environment, each essay adds depth and nuance to the project that Materiality advances: a profound acknowledgment and rethinking of one of the basic properties of being human.Contributors. Matthew Engelke, Webb Keane, Susanne Küchler, Bill Maurer, Lynn Meskell, Daniel Miller, Hirokazu Miyazaki, Fred Myers, Christopher Pinney, Michael Rowlands, Nigel Thrift  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aMaterial culture. 0aMaterialism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aMaurer, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinney, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelke, Matthew1 aMyers, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiyazaki, Hirokazu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeskell, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelke, Matthew, econtri